at professional treatment is needed according to modern criteria. His gallery of heroes includes the hubristic Otello and Godunov, the psychopathic Iago and Claggart, the schizoid Wozzeck and Grimes, the borderline Werther and Herman, the narcissistic Don Giovanni and Onegin, and the repressed and melancholic Faust and Aschenbach. Each is considered within the overall design of their respective work. Cordingly also probes the reception of each opera and draws comparisons with cases from life. The book is a landmark in being the first of its kind and weaves a fascinating tapestry of concerns. It is also eminently readable. JOHN CORDINGLY (author) is a Fellow of the Royal College of Psychiatrists. CLAIRE SEYMOUR (editor) is Head of Senior College at Queen's College London and the author of The Operas of Benjamin Britten [Boydell Press].  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHeroes in operaxPsychological aspects. 0aOperaxPsychological aspects. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh  aByronism.  acharacter analysis.  acultural contexts.  amental disorder.  amental health.  aopera.  aoperatic analysis.  aoperatic heroes.  apersonality disorder.  aprofessional treatment.  apsychiatric report.  apsychological analysis.  asexuality.1 aSeymour, Claire, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSeymour, Claire, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978099337741940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780993377419423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780993377419/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles